From now on, I will test backward compatibility with reference to Wiki's information.
BTW, do I need to fix the test class?

I think you can add this test to LuceneEventListenerJUnitTest and just flip the flag to false and assertFalse for the reverse case:

@Test
  public void pdxReadSerializedFlagShouldBeResetBackToOriginalValueAfterProcessingEvents() {
    boolean originalPdxReadSerialized = DefaultQuery.getPdxReadSerialized();
    try {
      DefaultQuery.setPdxReadSerialized(true);
      LuceneEventListener lel = new LuceneEventListener(null);
      final boolean process = lel.process(new LinkedList());
      assertTrue(DefaultQuery.getPdxReadSerialized());
    }
    finally {
      DefaultQuery.setPdxReadSerialized(originalPdxReadSerialized);
    }
  }

@jdeppe-pivotal - You're right, that should have been "does *not* work". I fixed the comment.

That MBean controller is doing crazy stuff with com.sun.tools.attach.VirtualMachine, fishing for JDK jars in the java.home of the remote process, and loading a com.sun management agent. I don't really know how to turn that into code that is going to work consistently across JDKs versions let alone with other JVM vendors. 

I think it would be a good idea to throw that code away but I don't know what the impact of that would be. My goal with this change was just to get us to the point where uses can run examples under JDK 9.
